\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces Study~A held-out confusion matrix aggregated over 5-fold cross-validation ($n=900$). Values are row-normalized percentages. UP (72\%) and SILENCE (75\%) are the most separable classes; RIGHT (33\%) is the worst, indicating that the under-chin placement captures tongue root motion but not the tongue tip curl required for the RIGHT command. The diffuse off-diagonal distribution is consistent with the signal crosstalk hypothesis.}}{7}{figure.caption.12}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:confusion}{{3}{7}{Study~A held-out confusion matrix aggregated over 5-fold cross-validation ($n=900$). Values are row-normalized percentages. UP (72\%) and SILENCE (75\%) are the most separable classes; RIGHT (33\%) is the worst, indicating that the under-chin placement captures tongue root motion but not the tongue tip curl required for the RIGHT command. The diffuse off-diagonal distribution is consistent with the signal crosstalk hypothesis}{figure.caption.12}{}}
